metadata.name: Hamiltonian Chaos Rug #20
metadata.description:
For my contribution to the #genuary32nd event I decided to mint a generative token based on my #genuary21 (Persian Rug) interpretation.

The images are generated iterating a discrete map on the plane obtaining the Poincaré section of an higher dimensional dynamical system. In this case the dynamical system is a simple periodically kicked harmonic oscillator.

The symmetry in the generated images in some way resembles those seen in middle eastern tapestry.

The palettes used are a subset of the Studio Yorktown Color Town Hall MIT licensed palettes.

It is possible to explore the map zooming in and out and saving the results in 2K and 4K resolutions.

Interactivity:
[z] to zoom in
[x] to zoom out

Default resolution: 2000x2000

[2] to redraw at double resolution (4000x4000)
[1] to redraw at default resolution
[s] to save a png at current resolution

It is possible to interact and save only when iterations stop.

Sources of variations:
- 28 palettes
- 4 kinds of symmetries (4, 5, 6, 7-fold)
- Several values for scale factor (20 - 80)

Developed with p5.js and chroma.js library

Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see License.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Hexaëder #51
metadata.description:
Hexaëder (cube) is a research into abstraction and a search for a balance between simplification and visual complexity.

No matter how simple and unambiguous things appear to be, in reality they are often more complex. Enjoy the simple, explore the complex.

Hexaeder has a wide variety of possible outcomes. I have put together 10 different color palettes; the number of cubes ranges from 10 to 401 (18 different grids); each cell can have 4 different background patterns; each cube can be filled in 4 distinct ways; there are 5 line colors and 16 different "cube figures"; the vignette can be black or be the color of the palette, and there are several "texture settings". This results in over 1.8 million possibilities.

For more information see: https://www.behance.net/gallery/131114761/Hexaeder-Flattened-cubes

metadata.name: A Slight Case of Overbombing #16
metadata.description:
Inspired by monochromatic art of the late 60s, Russian folk-art woodblock prints, and the stylised colours of British underground comics, excited to introduce a series of bold rich landscapes. England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland represented by red, yellow, green and blue, sometimes a house or two, and groovy clouds.

Instructions ::

.     - speed up
,     - slow down
space - pause
n     - toggle noise
p     - cycle palette
h     - toggle high-res (and definitely intentional pixel shift)
s     - download and save image
